trained to be a fighter in the hardship,

41:25.027 --> 41:40.266
That has one hell of a motivation

41:25.027 --> 41:40.266
in building tenacity

41:25.027 --> 41:40.266
in the individual

41:25.027 --> 41:40.266
towards surviving. You said earlier in this 
interview that you respected the German soldier

41:42.789 --> 41:52.941
even though you beat him. Did you respect the 
Vietnamese enemy and General Guillem?

42:09.851 --> 42:17.759
I respected him as a soldier, but I didn't think he 
was so great as everybody else thought he might be.

42:19.781 --> 42:23.805
Because when he came down conventionally for the 
first time, I destroyed him without American

42:25.000 --> 42:28.024
ground troops. I destroyed him totally with 
tactical air power and Vietnamese and a handful of

42:30.568 --> 42:42.304
American advisors

42:30.568 --> 42:42.304
and American air power.

42:45.829 --> 42:54.822
He should have been able to foresee

42:45.829 --> 42:54.822
after looking at capability of Americans to put in 
firepower, or the American availability of

42:55.325 --> 43:09.284
firepower,

42:55.325 --> 43:09.284
he should have been able to made a better judgment 
than he did. So, I respect him as a soldier, but

43:09.304 --> 43:20.539
he had no damn business of trying to set up his 
southern governmental headquarters in my area,

43:22.645 --> 43:26.671
in my ballpark. So he's pretty stupid as far as I'm 
concerned. Now, he might have done that in

43:32.339 --> 43:35.845
somebody else's ballpark, but not mine.

43:39.049 --> 43:40.552
Maybe he didn't respect the enemy. I don't think he 
did. He knew who I was, though. He did? Oh, yeah. How

